If you can't measure the impact of change (you don't have access to a simulation or observation environment), you can still apply the distortions and then check for compliance with types of prediction distortion patterns, distortion change patterns, variable patterns, etc.

div.b: Inference about System Context Given Alternatives

div.div: It's possible to measure what changes will reveal which paths were taken to arrive at an output - and different changes would be allowed in different systems.
A system that didn't allow function chaining would require the straight line path.
A system with the concept of chaining, order, position, or angle might allow the path with three functions.
A newer system would be likelier to have fewer distortion functions, lower complexity, and fewer assumptions/limits built-in.
With just the information of two possible paths, you've derived:

Once you have information about the system context (or you've inferred probable system information if not the information itself), you can better reduce the possible causes of a relationship, object, or attribute.

div.b: Example of deriving path from side effect prediction

div.div: If someone has a different intent, their paths may have side effects that wouldn't result from another path with different intents, even if the two agents have the same output position.

For example, if someone prioritizes not being criticized, that will leave traces that prioritizing improving the functionality of the weakest nodes would not - even if they both have a same output of being un-criticizable.
They have one output in common (not being criticizable) and their paths have some nodes/functions in common
(improving weakest node functionality), but one path leaves traces that the other path does not.
If you start from the priority of not being criticized, you will have arguments that protect you from criticism.
If you start from the priority of improving functionality of other nodes, you will have arguments for why they should use the improvement, how to deploy it, etc.
The starting point will leave traces in the functionality developed first/best.
Both paths will result in improving the functionality of nodes, and have the same output position of having improved other nodes (being uncriticizable).

But the agent that prioritizes being uncriticizable may have gaps in the functionality they've developed, and at what time this functionality was clearly building their decisions - if they only built the functions for improving others' functionality recently, that will be clear from their decision history (earlier decisions were clearly made without those functions).

div.div: The system limits may force someone prioritizing uncriticazbility to move in certain directions that they ordinarily would not if left to make their own decisions in a vacuum. They start from a selfish priority, moving in the direction of being uncriticizable and building functions to enable that intent, and by the system they're operating in, they're forced to move in other directions (making a gesture of charity, copying agent with priority of improving functionality of other nodes), while still having the same intent.

The agent prioritizing being uncriticizable will have pivot/angle/rotation functions/concepts, and their early decisions will reflect that, and the agent prioritizing improving other nodes' functionality will have cooperation, sharing, problem-solving functions and their decisions will be buildable with those functions at all stages.

This is an example of how different intents can not only have the same output, but the same trajectory at various points, while still leaving traces in their side effects (functionality developed to serve different intents at different stages of development).

div.div: This means you could predict the side effects of various intents & then look for those side effects, rather than deriving the various trajectories for each intent. This is similar to checking metadata of a solution rather than deriving the whole solution.
You could also predict side effects from a trajectory of functions.

div.b: Predicting Intent from Functions or Outputs

div.div: All outputs of a function are possible intents but adjacent objects to the outputs are possible intents as well - a point near the output that could have been expected or intended to be traversed to next by an attacker might have been the intended output position. The function output position would then be an interim output before the final output in red - or the attacker might have expected the output to be the malicious output given their understanding of its side effects.

div.div: When an abstract attribute has a structure applied to one of the definitions in its network, that structure can be computed as a proxy for that attribute, and the other definitions in its network may gather to form the complete abstract definition, to equal the abstract definition.
Difference types of an abstract attribute emerge in different ways.

Relevance is related to equivalence, which when cascaded to the structural or information interface, is representable as the concept of similarity, then some measure of connectivity (number & strength of connections) and distance.

The relevance of the 4 molecules is low, but there is relevance in the content (two equivalent molecules of each element, and in distance (the OH pairs are adjacent, which has a high similarity signal).

The benzene ring has more relevance, because it's not only comprised of the same element, but it has an extra connection between the two bottom carbon molecules, which increases the relevance of those two molecules.

By navigating abstract networks, you can identify which structural attributes are associated with the abstract attributes (if they're not already connected in your network) and use those structural attributes to approximate the abstract attribute score.
How would you identify that connectivity, commonness, distance & so on are good measurements of relevance?

First you'd standardize your definition of relevance, which should give you keywords like 'importance' and 'similarity' and 'cause'. These concepts exist on the interim layer between the abstract relevance concept and the useful structural attributes you can use as a proxy to measure the abstract concept. To link that interim conceptual layer to the structural layer, you'd look for structural attributes/rules/objects with rules using these attributes or similarities to these attributes.

You'd find similarities between the structural attribute 'commonness' and the interim concept 'importance', for example, because objects that are more common tend to have more of an impact, although not always.

Connection count & connection paths between two objects are also a good measure of relevance between together they measure connectivity, which is a proxy for causative importance (in the form of number of interactions with other objects and number of alternative paths between objects, indicating the possibility that many alternative paths evolved in the system because it's important that one object can get to the other, so many backups evolved.
Distance has attributes in common with similarity/difference, a proxy for the concept of equivalence (in a context)
- specifically attributes like "identification potential", "differentiation potential", "grouping potential" or the associated functionality.

Condition uniqueness is a measure of whether the system structure/inputs are likelier to be the more important cause, or whether the relationship between two objects is likely to generate or represent the relevance.
